# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tqdm-progress
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:tqdm-progress/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In computer programming, an **iterator** is an object that progressively provides access to each item of a collection, in order.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] A collection may provide multiple iterators via its interface that provide items in different orders, such as forwards and backwards.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An iterator is often implemented in terms of the structure underlying a collection implementation and is often tightly coupled to the collection to enable the operational semantics of the iterator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An iterator is behaviorally similar to a database cursor.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators date to the CLU programming language in 1974.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An iterator provides access to an element of a collection (*element access*) and can change its internal state to provide access to the next element (*element traversal*).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] It also provides for creation and initialization to a first element and indicates whether all elements have been traversed.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In some programming contexts, an iterator provides additional functionality.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An iterator allows a consumer to process each element of a collection while isolating the consumer from the internal structure of the collection.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The collection can store elements in any manner while the consumer can access them as a sequence.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In object-oriented programming, an iterator class is usually designed in tight coordination with the corresponding collection class.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Usually, the collection provides the methods for creating iterators.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] A loop counter is sometimes also referred to as a loop iterator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] A loop counter, however, only provides the traversal functionality and not the element access functionality.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] One way of implementing an iterator is via a restricted form of coroutine, known as a generator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] By contrast with a subroutine, a generator coroutine can *yield* values to its caller multiple times, instead of returning just once.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Most iterators are naturally expressible as generators, but because generators preserve their local state between invocations, they're particularly well-suited for complicated, stateful iterators, such as tree traversers.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] There are subtle differences and distinctions in the use of the terms "generator" and "iterator", which vary between authors and languages.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In Python, a generator is an iterator constructor: a function that returns an iterator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An **internal iterator** is a higher-order function (often taking anonymous functions) that traverses a collection while applying a function to each element.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Some object-oriented languages such as C#, C++ (later versions), Delphi (later versions), Go, Java (later versions), Lua, Perl, Python, Ruby provide an intrinsic way of iterating through the elements of a collection without an explicit iterator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An iterator object may exist, but is not represented in the source code.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An implicit iterator is often manifest in language syntax as `foreach`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] This iteration style is sometimes called "internal iteration" because its code fully executes within the context of the iterable object (that controls all aspects of iteration), and the programmer only provides the operation to execute at each step (using an anonymous function).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Sometimes the implicit hidden nature is only partial.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The C++ language has a few function templates for implicit iteration, such as `for_each()`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] These functions still require explicit iterator objects as their initial input, but the subsequent iteration does not expose an iterator object to the user.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators are a useful abstraction of input streams – they provide a potentially infinite iterable (but not necessarily indexable) object.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Several languages, such as Perl and Python, implement streams as iterators.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In Python, iterators are objects representing streams of data.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Alternative implementations of stream include data-driven languages, such as AWK and sed.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Instead of using an iterator, many languages allow the use of a subscript operator and a loop counter to access each element.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The ability of a collection to be modified while iterating through its elements has become necessary in modern object-oriented programming, where the interrelationships between objects and the effects of operations may not be obvious.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] By using an iterator one is isolated from these sorts of consequences.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] This assertion must however be taken with a grain of salt, because more often than not, for efficiency reasons, the iterator implementation is so tightly bound to the collection that it does preclude modification of the underlying collection without invalidating itself.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] For collections that may move around their data in memory, the only way to not invalidate the iterator is, for the collection, to somehow keep track of all the currently alive iterators and update them on the fly.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Since the number of iterators at a given time may be arbitrarily large in comparison to the size of the tied collection, updating them all will drastically impair the complexity guarantee on the collection's operations.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] But this approach will negatively impact the iterator performance, since it must effectuate a double pointer following to access the actual data element.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] This is usually not desirable, because many algorithms using the iterators invoke the iterators data access operation more often than the advance method.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] It is therefore especially important to have iterators with very efficient data access.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] All in all, this is always a trade-off between security (iterators remain always valid) and efficiency.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Most of the time, the added security is not worth the efficiency price to pay for it.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Using an alternative collection (for example a singly linked list instead of a vector) would be a better choice (globally more efficient) if the stability of the iterators is needed.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators can be categorised according to their functionality.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Different languages or libraries used with these languages define iterator types.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The enumerator initially points to a special value before the first element, so a call to `MoveNext()` is required to begin iterating.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Enumerators are typically obtained by calling the `GetEnumerator()` method of an object implementing the `IEnumerable` interface. a `Current` property, to obtain the value of the element currently being pointed at;Container classes typically implement this interface.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] However, the foreach statement in C# can operate on any object providing such a method, even if it does not implement `IEnumerable` (duck typing).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Both interfaces were expanded into generic versions in .NET 2.0.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators do not exist natively in C, but can be somewhat emulated with pointer arithmetic.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The following demonstrates a linked list of `int` with iterator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The C++ language makes wide use of iterators in its Standard Library and describes several categories of iterators differing in the repertoire of operations they allow.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] These include *forward iterators*, *bidirectional iterators*, and *random access iterators*, in order of increasing possibilities.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] All of the standard container template types provide iterators of one of these categories.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Traversal using iterators usually involves a single varying iterator, and two fixed iterators that serve to delimit a range to be traversed.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The distance between the limiting iterators, in terms of the number of applications of the operator `++` needed to transform the lower limit into the upper one, equals the number of items in the designated range; the number of distinct iterator values involved is one more than that.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] By convention, the lower limiting iterator "points to" the first element in the range, while the upper limiting iterator does not point to any element in the range, but rather just beyond the end of the range.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] For traversal of an entire container, the `begin()` method provides the lower limit, and `end()` the upper limit.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The latter does not reference any element of the container at all but is a valid iterator value that can be compared against.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The following example shows a typical use of an iterator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterator types are separate from the container types they are used with, though the two are often used in concert.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The category of the iterator (and thus the operations defined for it) usually depends on the type of container, with for instance arrays or vectors providing random access iterators, but sets (which use a linked structure as implementation) only providing bidirectional iterators.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Most containers also provide a separate `const_iterator` type, for which operations that would allow changing the values pointed to are intentionally not defined.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Simple traversal of a container object or a range of its elements (including modification of those elements unless a `const_iterator` is used) can be done using iterators alone.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] But container types may also provide methods like `insert` or `erase` that modify the structure of the container itself; these are methods of the container class, but in addition require one or more iterator values to specify the desired operation.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Implicit iteration is also partially supported by C++ through the use of standard function templates, such as `std::for_each()`, `std::copy()` and `std::accumulate()`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] When used they must be initialized with existing iterators, usually `begin` and `end`, that define the range over which iteration occurs.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] But no explicit iterator object is subsequently exposed as the iteration proceeds.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] This example shows the use of `for_each`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Since C++11, lambda function syntax can be used to specify to operation to be iterated inline, avoiding the need to define a named function.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Introduced in the Java JDK 1.2 release, the `java.util.Iterator` interface allows the iteration of container classes.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Each `Iterator` provides a `next()` and `hasNext()` method, and may optionally support a `remove()` method.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators are created by the corresponding container class, typically by a method named `iterator()`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The `next()` method advances the iterator and returns the value pointed to by the iterator.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The first element is obtained upon the first call to `next()`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] To determine when all the elements in the container have been visited the `hasNext()` test method is used.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] To show that `hasNext()` can be called repeatedly, we use it to insert commas between the elements but not after the last element.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] This approach does not properly separate the advance operation from the actual data access.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] If the data element must be used more than once for each advance, it needs to be stored in a temporary variable.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] When an advance is needed without data access (i.e. to skip a given data element), the access is nonetheless performed, though the returned value is ignored in this case.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] For collection types that support it, the `remove()` method of the iterator removes the most recently visited element from the container while keeping the iterator usable.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Adding or removing elements by calling the methods of the container (also from the same thread) makes the iterator unusable.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An attempt to get the next element throws the exception.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] An exception is also thrown if there are no more elements remaining (`hasNext()` has previously returned false).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Additionally, for `java.util.List` there is a `java.util.ListIterator` with a similar API but that allows forward and backward iteration, provides its current index in the list and allows setting of the list element at its position.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The J2SE 5.0 release of Java introduced the `Iterable` interface to support an enhanced `for` (foreach) loop for iterating over collections and arrays.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] `Iterable` defines the `iterator()` method that returns an `Iterator`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Some containers also use the older (since 1.0) `Enumeration` class.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] It provides `hasMoreElements()` and `nextElement()` methods but has no methods to modify the container.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In Scala, iterators have a rich set of methods similar to collections, and can be used directly in for loops.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Indeed, both iterators and collections inherit from a common base trait - `scala.collection.TraversableOnce`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] However, because of the rich set of methods available in the Scala collections library, such as `map`, `collect`, `filter` etc., it is often not necessary to deal with iterators directly when programming in Scala.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The `JavaConversions` object provides implicit conversions to do this.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Implicit conversions are a feature of Scala: methods that, when visible in the current scope, automatically insert calls to themselves into relevant expressions at the appropriate place to make them typecheck when they otherwise would not.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] MATLAB supports both external and internal implicit iteration using either "native" arrays or `cell` arrays.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In the case of external iteration where the onus is on the user to advance the traversal and request next elements, one can define a set of elements within an array storage structure and traverse the elements using the `for`-loop construct.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] traverses an array of integers using the `for` keyword.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In the case of internal iteration where the user can supply an operation to the iterator to perform over every element of a collection, many built-in operators and MATLAB functions are overloaded to execute over every element of an array and return a corresponding output array implicitly.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Furthermore, the `arrayfun` and `cellfun` functions can be leveraged for performing custom or user defined operations over "native" arrays and `cell` arrays respectively.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] defines a primary function `simpleFun` that implicitly applies custom subfunction `myCustomFun` to each element of an array using built-in function `arrayfun`.
