[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The simplest implementation is by wrapping an array, this can be useful for type hinting and information hiding.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] All methods of the example class are used during the execution of a complete foreach loop (`foreach ($iterator as $key => $current) {}`).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] `$iterator->valid()` returns *true* in this example.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] `$iterator->current()` returned value is stored in `$value`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] `$iterator->key()` returned value is stored in `$key`.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] `$iterator->next()` advances to the next element in the internal structure.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] `$iterator->valid()` returns *false* and the loop is aborted.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The next example illustrates a PHP class that implements the `Traversable` interface, which could be wrapped in an `IteratorIterator` class to act upon the data before it is returned to the `foreach` loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The usage together with the `MYSQLI_USE_RESULT` constant allows PHP scripts to iterate result sets with billions of rows with very little memory usage.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] These features are not exclusive to PHP nor to its MySQL class implementations (e.g. the `PDOStatement` class implements the `Traversable` interface as well).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators in Python are a fundamental part of the language and in many cases go unseen as they are implicitly used in the `for` (foreach) statement, in list comprehensions, and in generator expressions.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] All of Python's standard built-in collection types support iteration, as well as many classes that are part of the standard library.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators however can be used and defined explicitly.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] For any iterable sequence type or class, the built-in function `iter()` is used to create an iterator object.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The iterator object can then be iterated with the `next()` function, which uses the `__next__()` method internally, which returns the next element in the container.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] (The previous statement applies to Python 3.x.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] In Python 2.x, the `next()` method is equivalent.) A `StopIteration` exception will be raised when no more elements are left.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Any user-defined class can support standard iteration (either implicit or explicit) by defining an `__iter__()` method that returns an iterator object.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The iterator object then needs to define a `__next__()` method that returns the next element.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Python's generators implement this iteration protocol.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators in Raku are a fundamental part of the language, although usually users do not have to care about iterators.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Their usage is hidden behind iteration APIs such as the `for` statement, `map`, `grep`, list indexing with `.[$idx]`, etc.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Raku hashes can also be directly iterated over; this yields key-value `Pair` objects.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The `kv` method can be invoked on the hash to iterate over the key and values; the `keys` method to iterate over the hash's keys; and the `values` method to iterate over the hash's values.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] For any iterable type, there are several methods that control different aspects of the iteration process.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] For example, the `iterator` method is supposed to return an `Iterator` object, and the `pull-one` method is supposed to produce and return the next value if possible, or return the sentinel value `IterationEnd` if no more values could be produced.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] All iterable types in Raku compose the `Iterable` role, `Iterator` role, or both.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The `Iterable` is quite simple and only requires the `iterator` to be implemented by the composing class.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The `Iterator` is more complex and provides a series of methods such as `pull-one`, which allows for a finer operation of iteration in several contexts such as adding or eliminating items, or skipping over them to access other items.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Thus, any user-defined class can support standard iteration by composing these roles and implementing the `iterator` and/or `pull-one` methods.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The `DNA` class represents a DNA strand and implements the `iterator` by composing the `Iterable` role.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Ruby implements iterators quite differently; all iterations are done by means of passing callback closures to container methods - this way Ruby not only implements basic iteration but also several patterns of iteration like function mapping, filters and reducing.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Ruby can also iterate over fixed lists by using `Enumerator`s and either calling their `#next` method or doing a for each on them, as above.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Rust makes use of external iterators throughout the standard library, including in its `for` loop, which implicitly calls the `next()` method of an iterator until it is consumed.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Specifically, the `for` loop will call a value's `into_iter()` method, which returns an iterator that in turn yields the elements to the loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] The `for` loop (or indeed, any method that consumes the iterator), proceeds until the `next()` method returns a `None` value (iterations yielding elements return a `Some(T)` value, where `T` is the element type).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] All collections provided by the standard library implement the `IntoIterator` trait (meaning they define the `into_iter()` method).
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators themselves implement the `Iterator` trait, which requires defining the `next()` method.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Furthermore, any type implementing `Iterator` is automatically provided an implementation for `IntoIterator` that returns itself.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Iterators support various adapters (`map()`, `filter()`, `skip()`, `take()`, etc.) as methods provided automatically by the `Iterator` trait.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Users can create custom iterators by creating a type implementing the `Iterator` trait.
[src:tqdm-progress/iterator] Custom collections can implement the `IntoIterator` trait and return an associated iterator type for their elements, enabling their use directly in `for` loops.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] In computer programming, a **loop** is a control flow construct that allows code to be executed repeatedly, usually with minor alterations between repetitions.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Loops can be used to perform a repeated action on all items in a collection, or to implement a long lived program.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Loops are a feature of high-level programming languages.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] In low-level programming languages the same functionality is achieved using jumps.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] When a program is compiled to machine code, looping may be achieved using jumps; but some loops can be optimized to run without jumping.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Usually, loops are expected to run for a finite number of iteration.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Without proper care, loops may accidentally be created that have no possibility of terminating.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] The problem of determining whether a program contains an infinite loop is known as the halting problem.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A **conditional loop** (also known as an **indeterminate loop**) is a loop that determines whether to terminate based on a logical condition.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] These loops are flexible, but their exact behavior can be difficult to reason about.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A conditional loop is usually composed of two parts: a *condition* and a *body*.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] The *condition* is a logical statement depending on the state of the program and the *body* is a block of code that runs as long as the *condition* holds.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A common misconception is that the execution of the *body* terminates as soon as the *condition* does not hold anymore; but this is usually not the case.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] In most programming languages, the *condition* is checked once for every execution of the *body*.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] When the *condition* is checked is not standardized and some programming languages contain multiple conditional looping structures with different rules about when the *condition* is assessed.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A **pre-test loop** is a conditional loop where the *condition* is checked before the *body* is executed.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] More precisely, the *condition* is checked and if it holds the *body* is execute.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Afterwards, the *condition* is checked again, and if it holds the *body* is executed again.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This process repeats until the *condition* does not hold.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Many programming languages call this loop a *while loop* and refer to it with the keyword *while*.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Instead of the keywords *do* and *repeat*, other methods are sometimes used to indicate where the *body* begins and ends, such as curly braces or whitespace.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] For example, the following code fragment first checks whether *x* is less than five, which it is, so the *body* is entered.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] There, *x* is displayed and then incremented by one.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] After executing the statements in the *body*, the *condition* is checked again, and the loop is executed again.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This process repeats until *x* has the value five.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A **post-test loop** is a conditional loop where the *condition* is checked after the *body* is executed.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] More precisely, the *body* is executed and afterwards the *condition* is checked.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] If it holds the *body* is run again and then the *condition* is checked.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This is repeated until the *condition* does not hold.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This is sometimes called a *do-while loop* due to the syntax used in various programming languages, although this can be confusing since Fortran and PL/I use the syntax "DO WHILE" for pre-test loops.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Instead of the keywords *do* and *repeat* others methods are sometime use to indicate where the *body* begins and ends, such as curly braces.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Some languages may use a different naming convention for this type of loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] For example, the Pascal and Lua languages have a "*repeat until*" loop, which continues to run *until* the control expression is true and then terminates.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A **three-part for loop**, popularized by C, has two additional parts: *initialization* (loop variant), and *increment*, both of which are blocks of code.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] The *initialization* is intended as code that prepares the loop and is run once in the beginning and *increment* is used to update the state of the program after each iteration of the loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Otherwise, the three-part for loop is a pre-test loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This syntax came from B and was originally invented by Stephen C.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] The following C code is an example of a three part loop that prints the numbers from 0 to 4.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Assuming there is a properly declared function or method called `do_work()`, the following are equivalent in programming languages which support post-test loops.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Furthermore, given that a `continue` statement is not used, the above is technically equivalent to the following, though these examples are not typical or modern style used in everyday computers.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] An **enumeration** (also known as an **determinate loop**) is a loop intended to iterate over all the items of a collection.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] It is not as flexible as a conditional loop; but it is more predictable.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] For example, it is easier to guarantee that enumerations terminate and they avoid potential off-by-one errors.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Enumerations can be implemented using an iterator, whether implicitly or explicitly.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Depending on the programming language, various keywords are used to invoke enumerations.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] For example, descendants of ALGOL use `for`, while descendants of Fortran use `do` and COBOL uses `PERFORM VARYING`.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Enumerations are sometimes called "for loops," for example in Zig and Rust.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This can be confusing since many of the most popular programming languages, such as C, C++, and Java, use that term for the three-part for loop, which is not an enumeration.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] The order in which the items in the collection are iterated through depends on the programming language.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Fortran 95 has a loop, invoked using the keyword `FORALL`, that is independent of this order.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] It has the effect of executing each iteration of the loop at the same time.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This feature was made obsolescent in Fortran 2018.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] In most functional programming languages, recursion is used instead of traditional loops.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This is due to the fact that variables are immutable, and therefore the *increment* step of a loop cannot occur.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] To avoid running into stack overflow errors for long loops, functional programming languages implement tail call optimisation, which allows the same stack frame to be used for each iteration of the loop, compiling to effectively the same code as a *while* or *for* loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Some languages, such as Haskell, have a syntax known as a list comprehension, which is similar to enumeration, iterating over the contents of a list and transforming it into a new list.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A **loop counter** is a control variable that controls the iterations of a loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Loop counters change with each iteration of a loop, providing a unique value for each iteration.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] The loop counter is used to decide when the loop should terminate.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] It is so named because most uses of this construct result in the variable taking on a range of integer values.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A common identifier naming convention is for the loop counter to use the variable names *i*, *j*, and *k* (and so on if needed), where *i* would be the most outer loop, *j* the next inner loop, etc.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This style is generally agreed to have originated from the early programming of Fortran, where these variable names beginning with these letters were implicitly declared as having an integer type, and so were obvious choices for loop counters that were only temporarily required.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] The practice dates back further to mathematical notation where indices for sums and multiplications are often *i*, *j*, and *k*.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Using terse names for loop counters, like *i* and *j*, is discouraged by some since the purpose of the variables is not as clear as if they were given a longer more descriptive name.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Different languages specify different rules for what value the loop counter will hold on termination of its loop, and indeed some hold that it becomes undefined.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This permits a compiler to generate code that leaves any value in the loop counter, or perhaps even leaves it unchanged because the loop value was held in a register and never stored in memory.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Actual behavior may even vary according to the compiler's optimization settings.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Modifying the loop counter within the body of the loop can lead to unexpected consequences.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] To prevent such problems, some languages make the loop counter immutable.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] However, only overt changes are likely to be detected by the compiler.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Situations where the address of the loop counter is passed as an argument to a subroutine, make it very difficult to check because the routine's behavior is in general unknowable to the compiler unless the language supports procedure signatures and argument intents.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Some languages may also provide supporting statements for altering how a loop's iteration proceeds.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Common among these are the *break* statement, which terminates the current loop the program is in, and the *continue* statement, which skips to the next iteration of the current loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] These statements may have other names; For example in Fortran 90, they are called *exit* and *cycle*.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] A loop can also be terminated by returning from the function within which it is being executed.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] In the case of nested loops, the *break* and *continue* statements apply to the inner most loop.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Some languages allow loops to be labelled.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] These statements can then be applied to any of the loops in which the program is nested.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] An infinite loop is a loop which never terminates.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] This can be intentional, or the result of a logic error.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Systematically detecting infinite loops is known as the halting problem.
[src:tqdm-progress/loop-computing] Infinite loops are useful in applications which need to perform a repeated calculation until a program terminates, such as web servers.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] A **progress bar** is a graphical control element used to visualize the progression of an extended computer operation, such as a download, file transfer, or installation.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Sometimes, the graphic is accompanied by a textual representation of the progress in a percent format.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] The concept can also be regarded to include "playback bars" in media players that keep track of the current location in the duration of a media file.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] A more recent development is the **indeterminate progress bar**, which is used in situations where the extent of the task is unknown or the progress of the task cannot be determined in a way that could be expressed as a percentage.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] This bar uses motion or some other indicator (such as a barber's pole pattern) to show that progress is taking place, rather than using the size of the filled portion to show the total amount of progress, making it more like a throbber than a progress bar.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] There are also indeterminate progress indicators, which are not bar shaped.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] The concept of a progress bar was invented before digital computing.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] In 1896 Karol Adamiecki developed a chart named a *harmonogram*, but better known today as a Gantt chart.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Adamiecki did not publish his chart until 1931, however, and then only in Polish.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] The chart thus now bears the name of Henry Gantt (1861–1919), who designed his chart around the years 1910–1915 and popularized it in the west.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Adopting the concept to computing, the first graphical progress bar appeared in Mitchell Model's 1979 Ph.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] D. thesis, *Monitoring System Behavior in a Complex Computational Environment*.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] In 1985, Brad Myers presented a paper on “percent-done progress indicators” at a conference on computer-human interactions.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Myers' research involved asking people to run database searches, some with a progress bar and some without.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Those who waited whilst watching a progress bar described an overall more positive experience.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Myers concluded that the use of a progress bar reduced anxiety and was more efficient.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Typically, progress bars use a linear function, such that the advancement of a progress bar is directly proportional to the amount of work that has been completed.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] However, varying disk, memory, processor, bandwidth and other factors complicate this estimate.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Consequently, progress bars often exhibit non-linear behaviors, such as acceleration, deceleration, and pauses.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] These behaviors, coupled with humans' non-linear perception of time passing, produces a variable perception of how long progress bars take to complete.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] This also means that progress bars can be designed to "feel" faster.
[src:tqdm-progress/progress-bar] Finally, the graphical design of progress bars has also been shown to influence humans' perception of duration.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] A **terminal emulator**, or **terminal application**, is a computer program that emulates a video terminal within another display architecture.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Though typically synonymous with a shell or text terminal, the term *terminal* covers all remote terminals, including graphical interfaces.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] A terminal emulator inside a graphical user interface is often called a **terminal window**.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] A terminal window allows the user access to a text terminal and all its applications such as command-line interfaces (CLI) and text user interface (TUI) applications.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] These may be running either on the same machine or on a different one via telnet, ssh, dial-up, or over a direct serial connection.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] On Unix-like operating systems, it is common to have one or more terminal windows connected to the local machine.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Terminals usually support a set of escape sequences for controlling color, cursor position, etc.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Examples include the family of terminal control sequence standards that includes ECMA-48, ANSI X3.64, and ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In the early days of computing, with the advent of interactive computing, the prevailing model involved a central computer connected to multiple terminals.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] This configuration, known as the centralized or mainframe model, featured a powerful central computer that performed all the processing tasks, while terminals served as input/output devices for users to interact with the system.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] These systems were initially character based.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] A character-oriented terminal is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time, as opposed to a block-oriented terminal that communicates in blocks of data.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] It is the most common type of data terminal, because it is easy to implement and program.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Connection to the mainframe computer or terminal server is achieved via RS-232 serial links, Ethernet or other proprietary protocols.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Character-oriented terminals can be "dumb" or "smart".
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Dumb terminals are those that can interpret a limited number of control codes (CR, LF, etc.) but do not have the ability to process special escape sequences that perform functions such as clearing a line, clearing the screen, or controlling cursor position.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In this context dumb terminals are sometimes dubbed *glass Teletypes*, for they essentially have the same limited functionality as does a mechanical Teletype.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] This type of dumb terminal is still supported on modern Unix-like systems by setting the environment variable `TERM` to `dumb`.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Smart or intelligent terminals are those that also have the ability to process escape sequences, in particular the VT52, VT100 or ANSI escape sequences.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] When personal computers became ubiquitous in the 1980s, they offered the option of running software on the user's personal computer, providing an opportunity to replace the expensive and space consuming hardware terminals with something that had additional functions.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Immediately software became available, that could emulate the functions of the hardware terminals on a PC.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Examples of such software for DOS were Telix or Telemate, which was published in 1988 and could emulate a DEC VT102 terminal.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Workstations, usually running versions of Unix, also became common in the 1980s.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Unix systems usually provided access to the command line with locally-attached or dial-up terminals.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Unix workstations were designed to be used primarily through a graphical user interface (GUI); to provide access to the command line, the GUI included terminal emulator applications that behaved like locally-attached terminals.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Through the success of Linux on servers, especially running on data centers and cloud servers, the necessity of accessing remote computers through character-based terminal emulators remains.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators, such as xterm, implement additional features not present in the emulated terminal.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Additionally, programs have been developed to emulate assorted system console "terminals" such as the Sun workstation console and the Linux console.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Finally, some emulators simply refer to a set of standards, such as the standards for ANSI escape codes.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Such programs are available on many platforms, including DOS, Unix-like systems including Linux and macOS, Windows, and embedded operating systems found in cellphones and industrial hardware.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In the past, Unix and Unix-like systems used serial port devices such as RS-232 ports, and provided `/dev/*` device files for them.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] With terminal emulators these device files are themselves emulated by a pair of pseudoterminal devices.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] These in turn emulate a physical port/connection to the host computing endpoint – hardware provided by operating system APIs, or software such as rlogin, telnet or SSH, among others.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In Linux systems, for example, these would be `/dev/ptyp0` (for the master side) and `/dev/ttyp0` (for the slave side) pseudoterminal devices respectively.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] There are also special virtual console files like `/dev/console`.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In text mode, writing to the file displays text on the virtual console and reading from the file returns text the user writes to the virtual console.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] As with other text terminals, there are also special escape sequences, control characters and functions that a program can use, most easily via a library such as *ncurses*.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] For more complex operations, the programs can use console and terminal special *ioctl* system calls.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] One can compare devices using the patterns vcs ("virtual console screen") and vcsa ("virtual console screen with attributes") such as `/dev/vcs1` and `/dev/vcsa1`.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators also include escape sequences for configuring the behavior of the terminal to facilitate good interoperation between the terminal and programs running inside of it, for example to configure paste bracketing.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] The virtual consoles can be configured in the file `/etc/inittab` read by *init*—typically it starts the text mode login process *getty* for several virtual consoles.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] X Window System can be configured in `/etc/inittab` or by an X display manager.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] A number of Linux distributions use systemd instead of init, which also allows virtual console configuration.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement a local echo function, which may erroneously be named "half-duplex", or still slightly incorrectly "echoplex" (which is formally an error detection mechanism rather than an input display option).
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement local editing, also known as "line-at-a-time mode".
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] This is also mistakenly referred to as "half-duplex".
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In this mode, the terminal emulator only sends complete lines of input to the host system.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] The user enters and edits a line, but it is held locally within the terminal emulator as it is being edited.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] It is not transmitted until the user signals its completion, usually with the ↵ Enter key on the keyboard or a "send" button of some sort in the user interface.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] At that point, the entire line is transmitted.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Line-at-a-time mode implies local echo, since otherwise the user will not be able to see the line as it is being edited and constructed.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] However, line-at-a-time mode is independent of echo mode and does not *require* local echo.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] When entering a password, for example, line-at-a-time entry with local editing is possible, but local echo is turned off (otherwise the password would be displayed).
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] The complexities of line-at-a-time mode are exemplified by the line-at-a-time mode option in the telnet protocol.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] To implement it correctly, the *Network Virtual Terminal* implementation provided by the terminal emulator program must be capable of recognizing and properly dealing with "interrupt" and "abort" events that arrive in the middle of locally editing a line.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In asynchronous terminals data can flow in any direction at any time.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] In **synchronous terminals** a protocol controls who may send data when.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] IBM 3270-based terminals used with IBM mainframe computers are an example of **synchronous terminals**.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] They operate in an essentially "screen-at-a-time" mode (also known as block mode).
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Users can make numerous changes to a page, before submitting the updated screen to the remote machine as a single action.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators that simulate the 3270 protocol are available for most operating systems, for use both by those administering systems such as the z9, as well as those using the corresponding applications such as CICS.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Other examples of synchronous terminals include the IBM 5250, ICL 7561, Honeywell Bull VIP7800 and Hewlett-Packard 700/92.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles, also called virtual terminals, are emulated text terminals, using the keyboard and monitor of a personal computer or workstation.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] The word "text" is key since virtual consoles are not GUI terminals and they do not run inside a graphical interface.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles are found on most Unix-like systems.
[src:tqdm-progress/terminal-emulator] They are primarily used to access and interact with servers, without using a graphical desktop environment.
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] `tqdm` means "progress" in Arabic (*taqadum*, تقدّم) and is an abbreviation for "I love you so much" in Spanish (*te quiero demasiado*).
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] Instantly make your loops show a smart progress meter - just wrap any iterable with `tqdm(iterable)`, and you're done!
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] `trange(N)` can be also used as a convenient shortcut for `tqdm(range(N))`.
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] Overhead is low -- about 60ns per iteration (80ns with `tqdm_gui`), and is unit tested against performance regression.
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] By comparison, the well-established ProgressBar has an 800ns/iter overhead.
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] In addition to its low overhead, `tqdm` uses smart algorithms to predict the remaining time and to skip unnecessary iteration displays, which allows for a negligible overhead in most cases.
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] `tqdm` works on any platform (Linux, Windows, Mac, FreeBSD, NetBSD, Solaris/SunOS), in any console or in a GUI, and is also friendly with IPython/Jupyter notebooks.
[src:tqdm-progress/tqdm-github-io] `tqdm` does not require any dependencies (not even `curses`!), just Python and an environment supporting `carriage return \r` and `line feed \n` control characters.
